{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476798"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:52:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:52:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13952"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13952"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.2,0.19,0.05,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57929"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6582"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13952"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43388"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2623"},{"type":"tags","id":"2624"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57929"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy is admitted to hospital for treatment of severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID). He requires a blood transfusion as part of his management. The paediatrician orders irradiated blood products. On examination, he appears pale with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His most recent haemoglobin level is 75 g/L (110-145).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following complications is routine irradiation of blood products primarily intended to prevent in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alloimmunisation","Cytomegalovirus infection","Febrile non-haemolytic transfusion reaction","Transfusion-related acute lung injury","Transfusion-associated graft-versus-host disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary purpose of irradiating blood products for immunodeficient patients, such as this child with severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID), is to prevent \u003Cstrong\u003Etransfusion-associated graft-versus-host disease\u003C/strong\u003E (TA-GVHD). Irradiation inactivates T-lymphocytes in the blood product, which are responsible for initiating GVHD in the immunocompromised recipient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlloimmunisation\u003C/strong\u003E is the development of antibodies against foreign antigens, typically red blood cell antigens, following exposure through transfusion. While this is an important consideration in transfusion medicine, irradiation of blood products does not prevent alloimmunisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus infection\u003C/strong\u003E is a concern in immunocompromised patients receiving blood transfusions. However, prevention of CMV transmission is typically achieved through the use of CMV-negative or leukoreduced blood products, not through irradiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFebrile non-haemolytic transfusion reactions\u003C/strong\u003E are typically caused by cytokines in the blood product or recipient antibodies against donor leukocytes. While leukoreduction can reduce these reactions, irradiation is not specifically targeted at preventing them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfusion-related acute lung injury\u003C/strong\u003E (TRALI) is believed to be caused by antibodies in the donor plasma or by bioactive lipids that accumulate during storage. Irradiation of blood products does not prevent TRALI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while blood product irradiation is crucial for preventing TA-GVHD in immunocompromised patients, it does not significantly impact the risk of other transfusion-related complications. Other strategies, such as leukoreduction, careful patient selection, and appropriate blood product storage and administration, are used to mitigate these risks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Routine irradiation of blood products for immunodeficient children is primarily to prevent transfusion-associated graft-versus-host disease."],"references":["Transfusion-associated graft-versus-host disease (TA-GVHD). In: Australian Red Cross Lifeblood [Online]. Available from: https://www.lifeblood.com.au/health-professionals/clinical-practice/adverse-events/TA-GVHD","Kopolovic I, Ostro J, Tsubota H, Lin Y, Cserti-Gazdewich CM, Messner HA, et al. A systematic review of transfusion-associated graft-versus-host disease. Blood. 2015 Jul 16;126(3):406-14. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25931584/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43388"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13952"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43388"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T08:45:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T08:48:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6582"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57929"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"dat